Plotting pie chart¶

In [3]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
data=pd.read_csv("D:\\Internship Progress\\WEEK3 new updated\\WEEK3\\Hospitality\\lounge refresh.csv")
count_positive = 0
count_negative = 0
count_neutral = 0

for sentiment in data['sentiment']:
    if sentiment == 'Positive':
        count_positive += 1
    else:
        count_negative += 1
total=len(data)
positive_response= (count_positive / total) * 100
negative_response = (count_negative / total) * 100
myexplode = [0.2, 0]
y=[positive_response,negative_response]
plt.pie(y,labels=[str(round(positive_response,2))+"%",str(round(negative_response,2))+"%"],explode = myexplode, shadow = True,colors=["g","r"])
plt.title("Hospitality tweet % distribution")
plt.legend(["positive","negative"])
plt.show()

LDA for positive tweets¶

In [4]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation

from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the positive reviews data
positive_reviews = pd.read_csv("D:\\Internship Progress\\WEEK3 new updated\\WEEK3\\Hospitality\\lounge refresh - Copy.csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = positive_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Add your custom stop words to this list
stop_words = text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS.union(custom_stop_words)

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for positive reviews)


for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: access, security, hotel, hospitality, key, blrairport, facilities, flight, lounge, food
Topic 2: axis, terminal, list, experience, food, card, amp, credit, 080, lounge
Topic 3: airports, holders, mumbai, free, saw, entry, card, lounges, premium, lounge
Topic 4: buffet, cards, food, live, hotel, staff, service, time, gt, lounge
Topic 5: facility, 080, staff, place, blrairport, best, domestic, terminal, food, lounge

Observation on positive tweets¶

  • ### Passengers appreciate the convenience of airport lounges, such as the ability to use mobile wallets to pay for access, the availability of dedicated workspaces and meeting rooms, and the option to access lounges regardless of their airline or travel class.
  • ### Passengers value the comfort and relaxation that airport lounges offer, such as the availability of massage chairs, yoga rooms, meditation spaces, and a variety of local food and drinks.
  • ### Passengers appreciate the opportunity to network with other business travelers and learn about the local culture and cuisine in airport lounges.

Recommendations:¶

  • ### Continue to offer convenient and comfortable amenities, such as mobile wallet payments, dedicated workspaces and meeting rooms, and a variety of local food and drinks.
  • ### Partner with mobile wallet providers, airlines, and travel booking platforms to make it easy for passengers to access airport lounges.
  • ### Offer relaxation and wellness amenities, such as massage chairs, yoga rooms, and meditation spaces.
  • ### Partner with local businesses to showcase the local culture and cuisine in airport lounges.

Word cloud for positive tweets¶

In [5]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from wordcloud import WordCloud

# Create a word cloud object
wc = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_font_size=50)

# Check the type of the topics variable
if isinstance(topics, list):
    # Convert the topics variable to a list of strings
    topics = [" ".join(topic) for topic in topics]

# Generate the word cloud
wc.generate(" ".join(topics))

# Plot the word cloud
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.imshow(wc)
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Top Words in Positive Reviews")
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation

from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the negative reviews data
negative_reviews = pd.read_csv("D:\\Internship Progress\\WEEK3 new updated\\WEEK3\\Hospitality\\lounge refresh - Copy (2).csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = negative_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Add your custom stop words to this list
stop_words = text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS.union(custom_stop_words)

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for positive reviews)


for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: new, accepted, denied, left, terminal, 080, access, rupees, debit, card
Topic 2: card, denied, terminal, blrairport, left, cards, restricted, access, country, 080
Topic 3: debit, blrairport, new, denied, platinum, international, t2, terminal, card, access
Topic 4: blrairport, new, accepted, debit, card, denied, left, terminal, 080, access
Topic 5: 080, rupees, denied, t2, new, access, card, domestic, accepted, terminal

Observation on negative tweets¶

  • ### There are a number of negative tweets about debit cards being denied at Bangalore International Airport (BLR).
  • ### The tweets mention that the cards are being denied at both domestic and international terminals.
  • ### The tweets also mention that the cards are being denied at multiple terminals (T2 and T3).
  • ### The tweets do not mention the specific type of debit cards that are being denied. However, some of the tweets mention that the cards are new and platinum cards.

Recommendations¶

  • ### Bangalore International Airport (BLR) should investigate why debit cards are being denied at the airport.
  • ### BLR should work with the banks that issue the debit cards to resolve the issue.
  • ### BLR should provide clear and concise information to passengers about why their debit cards may be denied and what they can do to resolve the issue.
  • ### BLR should consider providing alternative payment options to passengers whose debit cards are denied.
